<div class="evidenceBorder">
  <h3><i class="mch-compass-2"></i> <img src="../../images/smart-1-1-compass-3.jpg" alt="Image of Compass" class="right ppic" />RELATE. Strategies to Enable Effective Implementation</h3>

<p>In this section, reflect on how you can implement this competency in your daily work. The following implementation strategies provide a framework for meaningful participation and shared decision-making.</p>
<h3>Tiered Approach</h3>
<p>These implementation strategies follow a <strong>tiered approach of widening circles of influence</strong>. Through this approach, MCH leaders utilize resources and tools to activate change within their organization, which in turn incorporates community members through systems of genuine collaboration.</p>
<p><img src="../../images/spheres-of-influence.png" alt="Implementation Model" width="1956" height="700"/></p>
<h3>Implementation Strategies</h3>

<button class="accordion"><i class="mch-light-bulb"></i> <strong>Self-Reflection Strategy. </strong>How to advance yourself as an MCH leader.</button>
<div class="panel">
  <p><strong>How to Advance Yourself as an MCH Leader (Self-Reflection Strategy)</strong>. Take 5 minutes to engage in thoughtful self-reflection on your professional role, responsibilities, and approaches. Use the MCH Navigator's <a href="../../assessment/index.php">Self-Assessment</a> to explore your capacity to recognize and amplify community voices, create welcoming spaces, and commit to continuous learning. This process involves identifying personal strengths and areas of growth in understanding community needs and developing more collaborative approaches to leadership.</p>
</div>

<button class="accordion"><i class="mch-book"></i> <strong>Information Strategy. </strong>How to find and use tools to help you.</button>
<div class="panel">
  <p><strong>How to Find and Use Tools to Help You (Information Strategy)</strong>. Community expertise is a critical source of knowledge for understanding community needs and developing effective interventions. Seek out narrative collections, community stories, community-led research, and participatory research that prioritize the voices of those most directly impacted by community challenges. Community-Based Participatory Research principles are valuable in this approach, emphasizing meaningful participation and sharing research responsibilities with community members.</p>
</div>

<button class="accordion"><i class="mch-university"></i> <strong>Organizational Strategy. </strong>How to activate your organization.</button>
<div class="panel">
  <p><strong>How to Activate Your Organization (Organizational Strategy)</strong>. Transforming organizational culture to value community expertise requires a comprehensive approach to shared decision-making and meaningful participation. Begin by developing protocols that appropriately<a href="https://www.chcs.org/resource/engaging-community-members-a-guide-to-equitable-compensation/"> compensate community members for their time and expertise</a>, creating decision-making structures that distribute responsibility appropriately. Implement  <a href="https://www.urban.org/sites/default/files/2022-12/Centering%20Transparency,%20Accountability,%20and%20Community.pdf">transparent feedback and accountability processes</a> that center community voices.</p>
  <p>Explore toolkits and resources that focus on collaborative leadership models, such as the <a href="https://collectiveimpactforum.org/resource/community-engagement-toolkit/">Collective Impact Forum's Community Engagement Guide</a> and the <a href="https://www.ncdhhs.gov/hmp-engagement-toolkit/open">HMP Provider Engagement Toolkit</a> for creating sustainable strategies for ongoing community input and leadership.</p>
</div>

<button class="accordion"><i class="mch-cogs"></i> <strong>Systems Strategy. </strong>How to incorporate partners.</button>
<div class="panel">
  <p><strong>How to Incorporate Partners (Systems Strategy)</strong>. Move beyond traditional partnership models to create systems of  collaboration that center community expertise and perspectives. Develop <a href="https://www.buildhealthyplaces.org/tools-resources/measure-up/shifting-power-to-communities-through-data/">data collection methods that prioritize community narratives</a>, create platforms for continuous community-led assessment, and design <a href="https://www.urban.org/sites/default/files/publication/103920/assessing-the-impact-of-community-level-initiatives_1.pdf">evaluation frameworks that measure impact from community perspectives</a>.</p>
  <p>Explore national and local initiatives that demonstrate effective approaches to community engagement through  <a href="https://communityscience.com/category/community-systems-change/">Community Science's Systems Change Resources</a>. </p>
</div>
    <button class="accordion"><i class="mch-globe"></i> <strong>Community Strategy. </strong>How to engage your communities.</button>
<div class="panel">
  <p><strong>How to Engage Your Communities. </strong>Recognize that community engagement is not a one-time event but an ongoing, reciprocal relationship built on trust, respect, and shared decision-making. Develop long-term partnerships that support community-led initiatives through resources like the <a href="https://resources.depaul.edu/abcd-institute/resources/Pages/default.aspx">Asset-Based Community Development Institute</a> and <a href="https://servicelearning.ctb.ku.edu/#:~:text=Our%20framework%20for%20community%20engagement,phase%20incorporates%20Engagement%20and%20Reflection.">Community Toolbox's Engagement Strategies</a>.</p>
  <p> Explore guides from the <a href="https://www.communitychange.org/wp-content/uploads/C3-Messaging-This-Moment-Handbook.pdf">Center for Community Change</a> that offer  approaches to community organizing.</p>
</div>
</div>  

      
<h2><i class="mch-light-bulb"></i> 8.3.2 PRACTICE</h2>
	  <div class="evidenceBorder">
	  <h3><i class="mch-bookmarks"></i> <img src="../../images/smart-1-1-reflect.jpg" alt="Image of Thought Bubble" class="right ppic" />REFLECT. Staying Motivated</h3>
	  <p>As you work through your growth in this competency, it&rsquo;s important to stay motivated. Here are some tips to help you maintain focus and productivity along the way:</p>
      <ul>
        <li><strong>Make learning active, not passive</strong>. Passive learning is where you try to absorb information and knowledge. It&rsquo;s based on the idea that you&rsquo;re an empty vessel waiting to be filled. But research shows that this isn&rsquo;t the best way to learn. We actually <em>construct</em> knowledge by integrating the new material with what we already know and have already experienced. So if you want to learn a new topic quickly and effectively, use as much active learning as you can.</li>
        <li><strong>Visualize yourself starting</strong>. Make yourself sit down and work, even if this is for just 20 minutes. See starting as a parallel process, like a plane on a runway. You may start slow, but you will still take off!</li>
        <li><strong>Communicate to others any difficulties and/or what you intend to do</strong>. This can help you engage with the process and identify the important tasks. Communication/externalization can help you to commit with immediate goals. You could also find out others&rsquo; points of view and tips.</li>
        </li>
      </ul>
      <p><img src="../../images/mch-smart-motivation-008.jpeg" width="1024" height="512" alt="Motivational image" /> </p>
	  </div>
